A `.md` file is plain Markdown content. It uses a separate plain-Markdown renderer and is not Beandown.

### What it is

A `.md` file is rendered to HTML at compile time and exposed as one generated constant:

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    content #String = "<rendered html>"
]

The renderer is CommonMark-compatible with GFM extensions. It is not the Beanstalk md renderer used by Beandown.

### What it is not

- It is not Beandown. Beanstalk template syntax is not interpreted.
- It has no captures, directives or declarations.
- It does not see same-directory module root constants or `@html` constants.
- It has no Beanstalk scope at all.

### Beanstalk syntax is not interpreted

- Double-dash is Markdown text, not a Beanstalk comment.
- Dollar-prefixed text is text, not a template directive.
- Double-bracket template bodies and single-bracket insertions are text, not template syntax.
- Template delimiters, insertions and directives are literal text.

### Compile-time imported content

The rendered HTML is a compile-time String constant. It folds before the importing file uses it. It is not a runtime value.

### Output type

The exported field is `content`, a compile-time String constant. It is the only generated member.

### Target and builder availability

Plain Markdown is available in HTML project builds. The renderer is registered by the HTML builder.

### File ownership and relative path

A `.md` file belongs to the module that contains its directory. It follows the same import path resolution as `.bst` and `.bd` files.

### Related concepts

- For import syntax see @#markdown-imports (Markdown imports).
- For renderer features see @#rendering-contract (Rendering contract).
- For choosing between formats see @#choosing-a-content-format (Choosing a content format).
- For Beandown see @../beandown/#beandown-files (Beandown files).